</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Changing the Subject of Formulae</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>As explained in Lesson 1-19 <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 19 d~?">section d</a>, the variable which appears on the left hand side of a formula is called the subject of the formula.<P>

<P>Often a formula is not in a suitable ‘form’ for you to work with easily.  It is normally advisable to change the subject of the formula to the variable in which you are interested.</P>

<P>We can change the subject of a formula in a similar way to solving an equation.   The new subject is treated like the unknown variable in the equation.  This idea is detailed in <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 19 e~?">1-19 section e</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 19 f 0~?">section f</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 19 g 0~?">section g</a>.   Try 
<a href="launch.htm#q0368">q0368</a>.</P>

<P>Move onto Lesson 1-25.   First consider <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 25 a 0~?">section a</a> and then <a href="launch.htm#q0035">q0035</a>.  Work through <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 25 b 0~?">section b</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 25 c 0~?">section c</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 25 d 0~?">section d</a>.   Try <a href="launch.htm#q0667">q0667</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0372">q0372</a>.</P>

<P>Four further formulae are considered on pages 13 and 14 of your lecture notes.</P>

